Column Comment.0: SEISMIC SET SUBTYPE: The seismic set type column is used to enforce arelationship between the SEIS SET supertype and its valid sub types. Values for thiscolumn must be the name of the table that is the valid sub type for this row of data.Valid entries include SEIS_LINE, SEIS_SEGMENT, SEIS_SURVEY, SEIS_PLAN,SEIS_WELL, SEIS_PROC_SET, SEIS_INTERP_SET or SEIS_3D.
Column Comment.1: SEISMIC PROCESSING SET: unique identifier for a set of data that will beprocessed as a unit. The processing set may be a single line, a portion of a line, agroup of lines, a 3D survey, a portion of a 3D survey or a compilation of several.Details about what seismic sets are being processed is captured in the table SEISPROC COMPONENT.
Column Comment.2: ACTIVE INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether this row of data is currently eitheractive / valid (Y) or inactive / invalid (N).
Column Comment.3: AREA ID: Unique identifier for any named area such as a country, province, projectarea, area of interest, offshore area, district etc.
Column Comment.4: AREA TYPE: Unique identifier for the type of area, such as country, state, AOI etc.
Column Comment.5: DESCRIPTION: Description of the processing set.
Column Comment.6: EFFECTIVE DATE: the date on which this row of data first came into effect from abusiness perspective.
Column Comment.7: END DATE: the date that processing on this set was completed.
Column Comment.8: EXPIRY DATE: the date on which this row of data is no longer in effect from abusiness perspective.
Column Comment.9: MAXIMUM LATITUDE: The NW latitude of the seis set bounding box
Column Comment.10: MAXIMUM LONGITUDE: The NW longitude of the seis set bounding box
Column Comment.11: MINIMUM LATTUDE: The SE latitude of the seis set bounding box
Column Comment.12: MINIMUM LONGITUDE: The SE longitude of the seis set bounding box
Column Comment.13: OBJECTIVE: The reason why you are doing the processing.
Column Comment.14: ORIGINAL PROCESSING INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether thisprocessing is an original processing. If this is a reprocessed set, this flag should beset to N and the REPROCESSED IND set to Y.
Column Comment.15: ROW_MANAGEMENT_GUID: This value may be used to provide a global uniqueidentifier for this row of data. Use of this column is not mandatory, but if used,optional PPDM NOT NULL and UNIQUE INDEX constraints provided in the datamodel DDL should be created.
Column Comment.16: PROCESSED FOR: Business associate that the processing was done for.
Column Comment.17: PROCESSING COMPANY: business associate that did the processing.
Column Comment.18: PROCESSING NAME: the name assigned to the set for processing.
Column Comment.19: PROCESSING STATUS: the status of processing, either for the step or the completeprocessing step. Could be waiting for data, complete, cancelled etc.
Column Comment.20: PROCESSING SET TYPE: the type of processing set, such as 3D set, reconprocessing etc.
Column Comment.21: REMARK: Narrative remarks relating to this row of data.
Column Comment.22: REPROCESSING INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether this processing is areprocessing of original data. If this is a reprocessed set, this flag should be set to Yand the ORIGINAL PROC IND set to N.
Column Comment.23: SOURCE: The individual, company, state, or government agency designated as thesource of information for this row.
Column Comment.24: START DATE: the date that processing started.
Column Comment.25: ROW CHANGED BY: Application login id of the user who last changed the row.
Column Comment.26: ROW CHANGED DATE: System date of the last time the row was changed.
Column Comment.27: ROW CREATED BY: System user who created this row of data.
Column Comment.28: ROW CREATED DATE: Date that the row was created on.
Column Comment.29: ROW_EFFECTIVE_DATE: A system assigned date that specified when a row of datais effective from a systems perspective. This may be the date that a row of data wasmade available to end users, for example.
Column Comment.30: ROW_EXPIRY_DATE: A system assigned date that specified when a row of data isno longer effective from a systems perspective. This may be the date that a row ofdata was no longer available to end users, for example.
Column Comment.31: PPDM ROW QUALITY: A set of values indicating the quality of data in this row,usually with reference to the method or procedures used to load the data, althoughother types of quality reference are permitted.
